  "author_association": "NONE",
  "body": "https://github.com/envoyproxy/envoy/blob/c481a8cd64ce81300dabd4aefd7851eb2b9fb5b9/source/common/filesystem/inotify/watcher_impl.cc#L39\r\n\r\nThe above line identifies the string *before* the \"last slash\" in the original path as the directory to use for a subsequent inotify_add_watch command for the root runtime symlink... as such, if the end user (ie: me :) ) tries to place the symlink in /, ie: \"/envoy_runtime => /var/run/envoy/runtime\" or whatever... the directory ends up as an empty string and this is the error you get from --mode validate:\r\n\r\n```\r\n[critical][main] source/server/config_validation/server.cc:48] error initializing configuration '/etc/envoy.json': unable to add filesystem watch for file /envoy_runtime: No such file or directory\r\n```\r\n\r\nWhich is hard to debug, because it's telling you the symlink doesn't exist, even if it clearly does.\r\n\r\nI can submit a patch for this later perhaps, but I don't have source checked out or a build env setup or anything, just using your docker container for an integration, so... I imagine it'll be super easy for an existing dev to make an update for this, should just be a few lines to detect when `last_slash == 0` and then if so, shortcut to explicitly setting `directory` to `/`.",
